Very nice job Amir! It definitely looks better than my 720x384 copy with higher bitrate (same AVC video codec). Thanks for sharing!
I just finished downloading it and decided to stop seeding immediately, though after over 32GB uploaded I’m not sure if it would count as a hit and run ;)

@shaaani, @Oblivilot & @eliassos  I agree :)

@Mobile264 This 'stupid looking like uploader' has to my knowledge a vast experience encoding Bollywood movies, a field where is very difficult to find Blu-Ray sources, so they often have to upscale DVDs. I think you should probably be thankful for him using some expertise on this one. Now allow me to tell you that if I were to see a 100x100 picture in a 1000x1000 display I'd use PhotoZoom to do the upscaling as it does it way better than any viewer software (it has, indeed, more complex upscaling algorithms than Photoshop). But that’s just me; I always prefer the best viewing experience possible. If you don’t, then please consider the upscaling superiority of professional encoding software over players before you start deciding what makes sense or what doesn’t.

@dapratsta You sure about that? Please try it before stating it. I’ve explained about upscaling vs. player but now that’s something else… a TV? I mean, seriously? Unless your TV is running an Intel processor the best upscaling technology on a TV out there is Sony’s X-Reality Pro engine, and wouldn’t be sufficiently good against a video properly upscaled on a computer.

@Redundantos it’s stated in the description that the source is DVD, but thanks for figuring out the upscaling, genius!
